lets see if we can improve the score using Principal Component Analysis

We will use PCA to find the best no of features for our dataset and use that to train our model

In [39]:
# creating PCA object and using it on data X
pca = PCA()
principalComponents = pca.fit_transform(X)
plt.figure()
plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
plt.ylabel('Variance (%)') #for each component
plt.title('Explained Variance')
plt.show()

Above graph show that 100% of the variance in dataset is covered by two components so we will just use two columns for training

In [42]:
# now doing Principal component analysis with just two components

principal_x = pd.DataFrame(new_data,columns=['PC-1','PC-2'])

In [70]:
grid_param = {
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
    'max_depth' : range(2,32,1),

    'min_samples_split': range(2,10,1),

    disp = plot_confusion_matrix(clf, x_test, y_test,
                                 display_labels= class_name,
                                 cmap=plt.cm.Blues,
                                 normalize=normalize)
    disp.ax_.set_title(title)

    print(title)
    print(disp.confusion_matrix)
